Pangée is thrilled to participate in the 20th edition of NADA Miami (@newartdealers), which will be held at Ice Palace Studios (November 30 — December 3, 2022). For the occasion, Pangée is delighted to show a duo presentation of Darby Milbrath (she/her, b.1985, lives and works in Toronto, Canada) and Vanessa Brown (she/her, b.1981, lives and works in Vancouver, Canada). Milbrath and Brown grew up in the West Coast Gulf of British Columbia, a fertile and sublime landscape that shaped their relationship to the land and that manifests in their art as recurring motifs.

Darby Milbrath (@darbymilbrath) is a self-taught painter whose practice is imbued by her past as a contemporary dancer and herbalist. Her expressionist paintings stem from memory and imagination, while the cyclical nature of ebb and flow, death, and rebirth are ongoing themes explored in her paintings. Vanessa Brown's (@vanessanabrown) art practice encompasses sculpture and installation. Brown's primary medium is steel, as the artist is interested in challenging its historical associations with industry, war, and monuments. Brown explores how iconography has been translated and altered over time. By raising these questions, Vanessa Brown's work explores how time, image, and place can hold simultaneous, and sometimes conflicting, worldmaking meanings. Echoing Milbrath's symbols and themes, the imagery in Brown's work draws from various sources, including landscapes, historical crafts, dream interpretation, feminized labour, gestures of comfort, and ideas of escape.
𓂃

Snowy Painting, 2022 
62 x 44” oil on canvas 

This painting is currently on view at Nada Miami @newartdealers @pangee.pangee 

Two figures dance in a silvery reverie. There is a hushed introspective quality in the muted palette. I like to imagine that one figure dances with the deity of the moon. This painting was inspired by a poem. 

A Hymn to the Moon

Thou silver deity of secret night,
Direct my footsteps through the woodland shade;
Thou conscious witness of unknown delight,
The Lover’s guardian, and the Muse’s aid!
By thy pale beams I solitary rove,
To thee my tender grief confide;
Serenely sweet you gild the silent grove,
My friend, my goddess, and my guide.
E’en thee, fair queen, from thy amazing height,
The charms of young Endymion drew;
Veil’d with the mantle of concealing night;
With all thy greatness and thy coldness too.

Lady Mary Wortley Montagu (1689-1762)

“Each of Darby’s spiritual experiences trickle into her paintings, the compositions blurring symbolic iconography and kaleidoscopic landscapes under layers of diaphanous paint applied over many prolonged sittings.”

Photography @racheltophamphotography

“With her eye most drawn to scenes in which nature outgrows humanity, she notes of her interest in painting figures who are ‘humbled or made small in the landscapes’. If, at first, her paintings appear entirely abstract, ghostly trails of a former human presence soon loom, with faces doubling as petals, or bodies as stems.”

oil on canvas, 122 x 92 cm, 48 x 36 inches

'[…..] Darby Milbrath doesn't have to look too far to find the nature she so desires. Her studio in Victoria, Canada fronts directly onto bountiful stretches of sea, allowing her complete absorption in the outside world. In order to paint, she describes a hunger to 'feel submerged by nature' that is akin to a dream-like state.'

Thank you to everyone who attended the opening of Marne Repulse, my solo exhibition @pangee.pangee from November 25th, 2023 to January 13th, 2024

“It takes me a few moments to see the girls because they are almost trees. The paintings have caught them in a state of in-between, as if halfway through undressing, mid-metamorphosis. The strictly human world lies discarded, blousy and needless. In Darby Milbrath’s blotched pansy-scapes, grounds are neither fore nor back. She has not flattened the vista, but rather, made the very distant feel prominent. The sky is at hand. Her flowers smear in stratocumulus clouds. Yellow advances, like a storm.” 
Text by @audreywollen
